======================================================================
PART 1: THE FIELD F₄ AND ITS STRUCTURE
======================================================================

F₄ = {0, 1, ω, ω²} where ω² + ω + 1 = 0 over F₂

Multiplication table:
   0 × : ['0', '0', '0', '0']
   1 × : ['0', '1', 'ω', 'ω²']
   ω × : ['0', 'ω', 'ω²', '1']
  ω² × : ['0', 'ω²', '1', 'ω']

Frobenius automorphism (x → x²):
  0² = 0
  1² = 1
  ω² = ω²
  ω²² = ω
  Fixed points of Frobenius = F₂ = {0, 1}

======================================================================
PART 2: PG(2, F₄) — THE 21-POINT PROJECTIVE PLANE
======================================================================

|PG(2, F₄)| = 21 points
Points of PG(2, F₄):
  P 0 = (0, 0, 1) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P 1 = (0, 1, 0) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P 2 = (0, 1, ω)
  P 3 = (0, 1, 1) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P 4 = (0, 1, ω²)
  P 5 = (1, 0, 0) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P 6 = (1, 0, ω)
  P 7 = (1, 0, 1) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P 8 = (1, 0, ω²)
  P 9 = (1, ω, 0)
  P10 = (1, ω, ω)
  P11 = (1, ω, 1)
  P12 = (1, ω, ω²)
  P13 = (1, 1, 0) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P14 = (1, 1, ω)
  P15 = (1, 1, 1) ← F₂ point (Baer)
  P16 = (1, 1, ω²)
  P17 = (1, ω², 0)
  P18 = (1, ω², ω)
  P19 = (1, ω², 1)
  P20 = (1, ω², ω²)

======================================================================
PART 3: THE 3 BAER SUBPLANES OF PG(2, F₄)
======================================================================

Baer subplane B₁ (F₂-rational points): [0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 13, 15]
  |B₁| = 7

Frobenius orbits (σ: x → x²):
  Fixed: P0
  Fixed: P1
  Orbit: P2 ↔ P4
  Fixed: P3
  Fixed: P5
  Orbit: P6 ↔ P8
  Fixed: P7
  Orbit: P9 ↔ P17
  Orbit: P10 ↔ P20
  Orbit: P11 ↔ P19
  Orbit: P12 ↔ P18
  Fixed: P13
  Orbit: P14 ↔ P16
  Fixed: P15

Fixed points (= B₁): [0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 13, 15] (7 points)
2-orbits: 7 orbits (14 points)
Total: 7 + 14 = 21

B₁ has 7 lines of 3 points = PG(2,F₂) ✓

Searching for Baer subplane partition...
  Found partition! mask=0
  B₂ = [4, 8, 17, 20, 19, 18, 16] (7 lines ✓)
  B₃ = [2, 6, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14] (7 lines ✓)

======================================================================
PART 4: I-POLYNOMIAL ↔ BAER SUBPLANE CORRESPONDENCE
======================================================================

INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL FACTORIZATION:
  I(K₁⊔K₃, x) = I(K₁, x) · I(K₃, x) = (1+x)(1+3x)
  At x=2: I = 3 × 7 = 21

BAER SUBPLANE DECOMPOSITION:
  PG(2, F₄) = B₁ ⊔ B₂ ⊔ B₃
  |PG(2, F₄)| = |B₁| + |B₂| + |B₃| = 7 + 7 + 7 = 21

THE CORRESPONDENCE:
  Factor 7 = I(K₃, 2) = |PG(2, F₂)| = |Baer subplane|
  Factor 3 = I(K₁, 2) = NUMBER of Baer subplanes

  K₃ component of Ω ↔ one Baer subplane (the cycle conflict structure)
  K₁ component of Ω ↔ the 'selector' choosing which subplane

  The I-polynomial factorization IS the Baer partition!

======================================================================
PART 5: SIMPLEX (x+1)^n, CUBOID (x+2)^n, AND PROJECTIVE PLANES
======================================================================

Evaluate at x = 2:
  (x+1)^n at x=2: 3^n (simplex polynomial)
  (x+2)^n at x=2: 4^n (cuboid polynomial)
  Complement C(n) = 4^n - 3^n

  n=1: C(n) = 4^1 - 3^1 = 1
  n=2: C(n) = 4^2 - 3^2 = 7 = |PG(2, F_2)| ← PROJECTIVE PLANE!
  n=3: C(n) = 4^3 - 3^3 = 37
  n=4: C(n) = 4^4 - 3^4 = 175 (div by 7)
  n=5: C(n) = 4^5 - 3^5 = 781
  n=6: C(n) = 4^6 - 3^6 = 3367 (div by 7)
  n=7: C(n) = 4^7 - 3^7 = 14197

STUNNING: C(2) = 4² - 3² = 16 - 9 = 7 = |PG(2, F₂)| = H_forb_1!
The complement of the simplex-in-cuboid at n=2 IS the Fano plane size!

And C(2) × 3 = 7 × 3 = 21 = |PG(2, F₄)| = H_forb_2
The three 'copies' are the three Baer subplanes!

======================================================================
PART 6: WHY THE PATTERN STOPS — THE BAER WALL
======================================================================

Projective planes over F_{2^k}:
  k=1: q=2^1=2, |PG(2,F_2)| = 7 [FORBIDDEN]
         Baer subplanes of PG(2,F_2²): |PG(2,F_2²)/7 = 3
         q² - q + 1 = 3
  k=2: q=2^2=4, |PG(2,F_4)| = 21 [FORBIDDEN]
         Baer subplanes of PG(2,F_4²): |PG(2,F_4²)/21 = 13
         q² - q + 1 = 13
  k=3: q=2^3=8, |PG(2,F_8)| = 73 [achievable]
         Baer subplanes of PG(2,F_8²): |PG(2,F_8²)/73 = 57
         q² - q + 1 = 57
  k=4: q=2^4=16, |PG(2,F_16)| = 273 [achievable]
         Baer subplanes of PG(2,F_16²): |PG(2,F_16²)/273 = 241
         q² - q + 1 = 241
  k=5: q=2^5=32, |PG(2,F_32)| = 1057 [achievable]
         Baer subplanes of PG(2,F_32²): |PG(2,F_32²)/1057 = 993
         q² - q + 1 = 993
  k=6: q=2^6=64, |PG(2,F_64)| = 4161 [achievable]
         Baer subplanes of PG(2,F_64²): |PG(2,F_64²)/4161 = 4033
         q² - q + 1 = 4033

THE BAER WALL:
  k=1: |PG(2,F₂)| = 7: FORBIDDEN (= Ω cannot be K₃)
  k=2: |PG(2,F₄)| = 21: FORBIDDEN (= 3 copies of forbidden)
  k=3: |PG(2,F₈)| = 73: ACHIEVABLE (escapes the wall)

Why? At k=1,2 the field F_{2^k} has 'too few elements' for
the Ω conflict graph to accommodate the projective structure.
At k=3 (F₈), there are enough elements (8) that tournaments
with enough vertices can achieve H=73.

======================================================================
PART 7: THE TRINITY — 3 BAER, 3 STRANDS, 3^n
======================================================================

THE NUMBER 3 APPEARS IN THREE STRUCTURAL ROLES:

1. BAER SUBPLANE COUNT:
   PG(2,F₄) = 3 × PG(2,F₂)
   21 = 3 × 7
   The 3 Baer subplanes partition the forbidden structure

2. PASCAL STRAND COUNT:
   Standard Pascal (2-strand): row sums 2^n → Fibonacci
   Trinomial Pascal (3-strand): row sums 3^n → tribonacci
   3 strands ↔ 3 Baer subplanes ↔ ternary triple classification

3. SIMPLEX VALUE:
   (x+1)^n at x=2 = 3^n = I(empty graph on n vertices, 2)
   = maximum possible I(G,2) for n-vertex graph
   = CEILING of the independence polynomial world

4. k-NACCI LIMIT:
   Weighted k-nacci with weight x=2 → limit ratio = 1+x = 3
   The limit IS the per-vertex simplex contribution

UNIFIED VIEW:
   3 = (x+1)|_{x=2} = |{Baer subplanes}| = |{Pascal strands}|
   = k-nacci limit at x=2 = the fundamental 'packing factor'

   When we 'pack' a simplex (x+1)^n into a cuboid (x+2)^n,
   the simplex captures 3^n of the cuboid's 4^n points.
   The complement 4^n - 3^n at n=2 gives EXACTLY the Fano plane size 7.
   The 3 Baer subplanes of PG(2,4) are the 3 'directions' of packing.

======================================================================
PART 8: WHY BAER STRUCTURE CANNOT BE Ω(T)
======================================================================

THEOREM (informal): The Baer subplane structure of PG(2,F₄)
is incompatible with tournament conflict graphs because:

1. Each Baer subplane = PG(2,F₂) = Fano plane
   = 7 points with S(2,3,7) incidence structure
   = every pair of points on exactly 1 common line

2. In Ω(T), the 'lines' would be sets of 3 mutually-conflicting
   odd cycles (3 cycles sharing a common tournament vertex).
   This is EXACTLY the K₃ structure that THM-201 prohibits!

3. So each Baer subplane requires K₃ substructures in Ω,
   which are impossible. And 3 Baer subplanes compound this.

4. Result: H = |PG(2,F₄)| = 21 is forbidden because the
   geometric structure REQUIRES tournament-impossible configurations.

