======================================================================

Lines of PG(2, F₄): 21
Points per line: {5} (expected {5})
Lines per point pair: {1} (expected {1})

Lines of PG(2,F₄) restricted to Baer subplane B₁:
  Lines meeting B₁ in ≥3 points: 7
  (A Baer subplane meets each line in 1 or q+1=3 points)

  Line-B₁ intersection sizes: {1: 14, 3: 7}
  (Expected: 7 lines meet in 3 points, 14 lines meet in 1 point)

======================================================================
PART 10: Φ₃(q) AND THE OCF — THE DEEPEST CONNECTION
======================================================================

The third cyclotomic polynomial Φ₃(q) = q² + q + 1:
  Φ₃(1) = 3   (= I(K₁, 2) = number of Baer subplanes)
  Φ₃(2) = 7   (= I(K₃, 2) = |PG(2,F₂)| = H_forb_1)
  Φ₃(3) = 13  (Fibonacci prime, not forbidden)
  Φ₃(4) = 21  (= I(K₁⊔K₃, 2) = |PG(2,F₄)| = H_forb_2)
  Φ₃(5) = 31  (Mersenne prime)
  Φ₃(6) = 43  (achievable)
  Φ₃(7) = 57  (= 3×19)
  Φ₃(8) = 73  (achievable)

OBSERVATION: Φ₃ at POWERS OF 2 gives projective planes over F_{2^k}:
  Φ₃(2¹) = 7   → FORBIDDEN
  Φ₃(2²) = 21  → FORBIDDEN
  Φ₃(2³) = 73  → achievable

The forbidden values are Φ₃(2) and Φ₃(4) = Φ₃(2²).
But Φ₃(2³) = 73 escapes. WHY?

ANSWER: The Baer subplane structure.
  PG(2,F₄) = 3 × PG(2,F₂): the subplane IS the forbidden structure.
  PG(2,F₈) cannot be decomposed into copies of PG(2,F₂) because
  F₈ is NOT an extension of F₂ via squaring (F₈ ≅ F₂[x]/(x³+x+1)).
  The Baer subplane of PG(2,F₈) would be PG(2,F_{√8}),
  but √8 is not a prime power — no subplane exists!

MORE PRECISELY: A Baer subplane PG(2,q) exists in PG(2,Q)
  iff Q = q². So:
  - PG(2,4) has Baer subplanes PG(2,2) ✓ (4 = 2²)
  - PG(2,8) has Baer subplanes PG(2,√8) ✗ (√8 not integer)
  - PG(2,16) has Baer subplanes PG(2,4) ✓ (16 = 4²)

So: |PG(2,16)| = 273 = Φ₃(16). Is 273 forbidden?
  PG(2,16) has Baer subplanes PG(2,4), each of size 21.
  But 21 is ITSELF forbidden, so the chain continues!
  273 = 21 × 13 = forbidden × ??
  Actually 273/21 = 13, and Φ₃(4) = 21, so 273 = 13 × 21.
  Number of Baer subplanes in PG(2,16): |PG(2,16)|/|PG(2,4)| = 273/21 = 13

OPEN QUESTION: Is H=273 = |PG(2,F₁₆)| forbidden?
  If yes: the Baer chain continues (PG(2,2) → PG(2,4) → PG(2,16))
  Each level contains the previous as a Baer subplane.
  This would give forbidden values at |PG(2, 2^{2^k})|:
  k=0: |PG(2,2)| = 7
  k=1: |PG(2,4)| = 21
  k=2: |PG(2,16)| = 273
  k=3: |PG(2,256)| = 65793
  These are the 'Baer tower' values!

======================================================================
PART 11: THE BAER SUBPLANE THEORY OF FORBIDDEN H
======================================================================

MAIN THEOREM (conjectural):
  H(T) ≠ |PG(2, F_{2^{2^k}})| for all tournaments T and all k ≥ 0.

PROOF SKETCH:
  Base case (k=0): H ≠ 7 = |PG(2,F₂)|.
    Proof: Ω(T) ≠ K₃ by THM-201 (K₃ requires a tournament vertex
    common to 3 directed 3-cycles in a Steiner-like arrangement,
    which forces additional cycles by dominance cascade).

  k=1: H ≠ 21 = |PG(2,F₄)|.
    The I-polynomial of any graph with I(G,2)=21 factors through
    the Baer subplane structure: either (1+3x) divides I(G,x)
    (the K₃ poison), or G ∈ {K₆-2e, K₈-e, K₁₀} which cannot be Ω(T)
    by structural constraints on cycle overlap in tournaments.

  k≥2: H ≠ |PG(2, F_{2^{2^k}})| (CONJECTURED).
    Each level inherits the impossibility from the previous via
    the Baer subplane containment PG(2,F_{q²}) ⊃ PG(2,F_q).

THE SIMPLEX-CUBOID NESTING INTERPRETATION:
  The forbidden values arise at the 'corners' of the simplex-in-cuboid
  packing. At n=2: the complement 4²-3²=7 is the Fano plane.
  The 3 Baer subplanes are the 3 'directions' along which the
  simplex touches the cuboid boundary.
  The k-nacci limit 3 = the number of these directions.

  (x+1)^n = simplex = 'achievable core'
  (x+2)^n = cuboid = 'total space'
  Complement = the 'forbidden shell' with projective structure!
